{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"29ca49be-4a55-4b2f-af29-92a944ad16f1","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` alone won't get you edge-to-edge on both platforms. You need two things:\n\n**1. iOS — ignore safe area insets on the page:**\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n\n<ContentPage ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**2. Android — enable edge-to-edge rendering** (system bars don't go transparent by default). Add this in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnCreate((activity, _) =>\n    {\n        var window = activity.Window!;\n        AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false);\n        window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**3. Make the image fill everything:**\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nThe core issue: on Android, the window must explicitly opt in to drawing behind system bars. On iOS, `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` is the correct platform-specific property (not `SafeAreaEdges`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"50beaad8-3721-4e99-a676-174a981eb037","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is building a .NET MAUI app and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar), but setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage isn't working. Let me think about what they need.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you typically need to:\n\n1. Set the page to ignore safe area insets — which they've done with `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` (this is an iOS concept primarily)\n2. But the key missing piece is likely that they need to opt into edge-to-edge display mode, especially on Android.\n\n\n3. On Android, particularly with Android 15+, apps are edge-to-edge by default, but on earlier versions you may need to explicitly enable it through platform-specific code or window settings. On iOS, ignoring safe area insets should handle it, but you might also need to ensure the system bars are transparent so content can actually render behind them. area is the key on Android — I need to check if there's a `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` equivalent or if platform-specific code is required to tell the window to draw behind system bars. Let me think through the exact .NET MAUI APIs for both platforms. Setting up platform-specific configuration... Setting up Android edge-to-edge mode...","outputTokens":2042,"requestId":"043D:3BF41F:141B479:1677684:6A027CCA"},"id":"d337494b-f2b3-4833-9b34-80f6d1e9a289","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:05:52.774Z","parentId":"e31385dc-f77b-48b0-97f9-2aebbfbaa7f4"}
